<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08136j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08136j">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08136j"> 136(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Bad &mdash; Wells &mdash; Spa</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>Our Spas</b> Early in 1914, shortly before the European War opened, the Spa Authorities of Baden Baden, Bad Ems, Bad Nauheim, Bad Neuenahr, Bad Pyrmont, Wiesbaden Wildbaa and Bad Wildungen, in West Germany, conjointly issued a pamphlet describing their different bath systems, treatment, and the ailments for which each particularly catered.<font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Early last year the Great Western Railway of England sent out a more elaborate booklet, with descriptions and illustrations of Bath, Cheltenham, Church-Stretton <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Buith Wells, Llangammarch Wells, Llandrindod Wells, and Llanwyrtyd Wells. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Reading these attractive pamphlets one cannot help wondering why Ireland is so backward in exploiting her spas and health resorts. <small> <a name="TL9feb24" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#TL9feb24"><cite title="source">The Leader</cite></a> (9 February 1924) 16/1-2</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
